You are a quality attribute taxonomy expert reviewing a list of elicited quality attributes for a software system.

Your task: identify semantic duplicates, aliases, and sub-attributes that should be merged into canonical quality attribute groups.

SYSTEM CONTEXT:
  System: {{ system_name or "unknown" }}
  Workshop phase: {{ workshop_phase }}

ATTRIBUTES TO REVIEW:
{{ attributes | tojson(indent=2) }}

CANONICAL QUALITY ATTRIBUTES (the only valid top-level categories):
  availability, performance, security, modifiability, scalability,
  testability, deployability, usability, interoperability, data_integrity,
  auditability, recoverability, cost, other

DEDUPLICATION RULES:
  1. "resilience", "fault tolerance", "high availability" are aliases of "availability"
  2. "latency", "throughput", "response time" are sub-concerns of "performance"
  3. "disaster recovery", "backup and restore", "RTO/RPO" are sub-concerns of "recoverability"
  4. "authentication", "authorisation", "encryption" are sub-concerns of "security"
  5. "logging", "traceability", "monitoring", "observability" are sub-concerns of "auditability"
  6. "maintainability", "extensibility" are aliases of "modifiability"
  7. Two attributes with the same canonical category AND overlapping descriptions are duplicates
  8. An attribute is a sub-concern (not a duplicate) when its scope is clearly narrower
     than the canonical category — e.g. "encryption at rest" is narrower than "security"
  9. Do NOT merge attributes when they have distinct scenario response measures
     (e.g. "99.9% uptime" and "recovery in < 4 hours" target different outcomes)

CONSOLIDATION RULES (semantic merges):
  Only merge attributes when they would be addressed by EXACTLY the same design decisions.
  If two attributes would require different architectural tactics to achieve them,
  they are distinct and must NOT be merged.

  Examples of attributes that look similar but are distinct:
    Availability vs Recoverability — different tactics (redundancy vs checkpoint/restart)
    Performance vs Scalability — different tactics (optimisation vs horizontal partitioning)
    Auditability vs Observability — different artifacts (audit logs vs operational metrics)
    Data Integrity vs Security — different concerns (correctness vs access control)

  When in doubt, keep them separate. Over-merging destroys architectural signal.
  Under-merging can be corrected later. Over-merging cannot be recovered from.

NON-QA CONCERNS to identify (these should be separated, not merged):
  Process/team concerns: team size, staffing, technical debt, agile process
  Pure business concerns: time-to-market, feature completeness, vendor lock-in
  Regulatory/compliance labels: GDPR, HIPAA, ISO 27001 (keep as sub-concern of auditability or security, not standalone)
  Infrastructure topology: multi-region, on-premise (these are tactics, not quality attributes)

